      {
        "id": "mineru_PPT_ch7_page_020_1",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Our examples show that in matrix products the order of factors must always be observed very carefully. Otherwise matrix multiplication satisfies rules similar to those for numbers, namely.",
        "bbox": [
          0.054,
          0.10755555555555556,
          0.8966666666666666,
          0.32355555555555554
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_PPT_ch7_page_020_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(a) (kA)B = k(AB) = A(kB) written kAB or AkB (2) (b) A(BC) = (AB)C written ABC (c) (A+B)C = AC+BC (d) C(A +B) =CA +CB provided A, B, and C are such that the expressions on the left are defined; here, k is any scalar. (2b) is called the associative law. (2c) and (2d) are called the distributive laws.",
        "bbox": [
